                    <h2 class="section-heading">ANIMALS</h2>
                    <p>In the past 100 years, nearly 500 species of animals have gone extinct. For every 10,000 species around the world, two of them die off every century. Of the 500 species that have gone extinct in the past 100 years, 158 of them were fish, 146 of them amphibians, 80 birds, 69 mammals and 24 reptiles. Experts have calculated between 0.01% and 0.1% of species go extinct every year. With the low estimate of the animals on our planet being 2 million species, 200 to 2,000 species will go extinct every year. <br> <br> There are many reasons that animals are going extinct, but nearly all of them are caused by humans. Poaching, polution, and deforestation are amongst them. That can only mean we need humans help to stop what we've begun. The things we've already done to this environment are irreversible but that doesn't mean we can't make an effort to help and save what we have now and prevent more harm in the future. </p>
